At 2:55, I went over and asked for a refill from the half-filled Champaign bottles. As I asked, the “manager” said it had turned to 3pm and was too late to refill. I subsequently saw them throw these very bottles away. I had signed my bill 15 minutes prior, and clearly the manager was no longer concerned with my business. Went to the Cubs game on May 7th and it was cold and windy. We left the game at the top of the 8th inning and went to the Brickhouse to warm up and watch the end of the game. Got there and there wasn't a seat, so we went the bar and bought a couple of beers and stood and watch the game. Bought a second round of beers and a table opened up, so we sat down. The server came by and told us we couldn't sit because that was for people ordering from the server. Well we didn't move so she told us again and we didn't leave . Bryant homered and the game was over so we left after we finished our beers. I can't believe you spend $32.0 plus tip and you can't get a sit when a table opens up because you didn't buy your drinks for a server. I go to eight to ten games a year and you can bet I will never go in there again. There are plenty of other place's we can go to.

After awhile, my family and friends realized that we couldn't hear each other any more unless we shouted. At first I asked my waitress, Kristen, if she could please have them turn it down a little.  After that didn't happen  I then approached the DJ and asked him to turn it down. After that didn't work  I then approached the hostess station downstairs and  asked. Finally we just got frustrated and left. So I  probably wouldn't go back. I  could understand the louder music if there was a dance floor,  but at best there should be music played at a reasonable volume so the patrons could enjoy conversing,  not yelling at each other. I don't get it  why you would want to make it unpleasant for your customers.  Saw in a couple other reviews the same complaints about loud music and owner apologized,  but yet nothing has changed.

Brunch Culture Lives Here.  Chicago is getting a name for itself as a brunch town.  Chicagoans will approach brunching the way Texans approach Texasing: proudly and without reservation. Brickhouse, a Four Corners Restaurant, is like an elevated sports bar on the inside -- high ceilings, dark industrial accents and LOADS of TVs -- plus a great 2nd floor outdoor patio overlooking the Park at Wrigley, outside of Wrigley Field. But that's not why there are five stars up there. Five stars comes from the breadth and depth of this brunch lineup -- much like the Cubs recent lineups. For $25, you get all you can eat MTO omelets, carving station and gourmet pancakes.. PLUS a fresh and abundant taco bar. PLUS an apps station.. PLUS a giant dessert spread.. PLUS a mac & cheese bar.. and it's ALL delicious.. but it doesn't stop there because included is also A BLOODY MARY AND ACCESS TO THE BLOODY MARY FIXINS AFTER YOUR VODKA IS GONE... or you can just order more. Or upgrade to bottomless mimosas with fresh pressed seasonal juices for $15 more. Oh.. and the coffee and hot chocolate bar is included too. I could sit there from 10am until 3pm eating if I had the ability to eat that much.  These guys aren't kidding around.  Just go.

Came here for NFL playoff game on Sunday at 2pm, was told we had to wait until 3:30pm if we wanted to order any food other than $35 brunch. Asked if we could put order in for 3:30 pm early and were told we could not, but server promised to come by at or just before 3:30pm. Around 3pm we noticed other tables near us were being served food from regular menu. We were able to finally flag down our server around 3:40pm, who shrugged off the other tables being served. I give 2 stars for the amount of televisions to view from almost any seat/angle, but forcing us to wait until 3:30pm because we didn't want to pay $35 each for brunch at 2pm will remind me to suggest a different sports bar next time my friends and I want to get together for a game.
